å®ä¾‹åŒ–å’Œåˆå§‹åŒ– Classes that only have behavior arenâ€™t super useful. The idea behind object-oriented programming is encapsulating behavior and state together. To do that, you need fields. Lox, like other dynamically typed languages, lets you freely add properties onto objects. breakfast.meat = "sausage";
breakfast.bread = "sourdough"; Assigning to a field creates it if it doesnâ€™t already exist. If you want to access a field or method on the current object from within a method, you use good old this. class Breakfast { serve(who) { print "Enjoy your " + this.meat + " and " + this.bread + ", " + who + "."; } // ...
} åªæœ‰æ–¹æ³•çš„ç±»ï¼Œä¸æ˜¯éå¸¸æœ‰ç”¨ï¼Œé¢å‘å¯¹è±¡èƒŒåçš„æ€æƒ³æ˜¯ï¼Œå°†è¡Œä¸ºå’ŒçŠ¶æ€å°è£…åœ¨ä¸€èµ·ï¼Œä¸ºæ­¤ï¼Œéœ€è¦å­—æ®µï¼ŒLoxå’Œå…¶ä»–åŠ¨æ€è¯­è¨€ä¸€æ ·ï¼Œå…è®¸ä½ åœ¨å¯¹è±¡ä¸Šè‡ªç”±æ·»åŠ å¯¹è±¡å±æ€§ã€‚ breakfast.meat = "sausage";
